{"title_page": "Lucien Lesna", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Lucien Lesna\n| image          = Lucien Lesna.jpg\n| caption        = Lesna c. 1898\n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1863|11|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Le Locle]], [[Switzerland]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1932|7|11|1863|11|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[\u00c9vreux]], France\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Lucien Lesna''' (11 October 1863 &ndash; 11 July 1932) was a French [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=4127 |title=Lucien Lesna |accessdate=14 April 2014 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He won the 1901 and 1902 [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] races.<ref name=\"ProCycling\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/Lucien_Lesna |title=Lucien Lesna |accessdate=14 April 2014 |work=ProCyclingStats}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|4127}}\n\n{{Paris\u2013Roubaix winners}}\n{{UCI Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lesna, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Le Locle]]\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Lucien Lesna\n| image          = Lucien Lesna.jpg\n| caption        = Lesna c. 1898\n| fullname       = \n| nickname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1863|11|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Le Locle]], [[Switzerland]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1932|7|11|1863|11|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = [[\u00c9vreux]], France\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Lucien Lesna''' (11 October 1863 &ndash; 11 July 1932) was a French [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"CyclingArchives\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingarchives.com/coureurfiche.php?coureurid=4127 |title=Lucien Lesna |accessdate=14 April 2014 |work=Cycling Archives}}</ref> He won the 1901 and 1902 [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] races.<ref name=\"ProCycling\">{{cite web |url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/Lucien_Lesna |title=Lucien Lesna |accessdate=14 April 2014 |work=ProCyclingStats}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|4127}}\n\n{{Paris\u2013Roubaix winners}}\n{{UCI Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lesna, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Le Locle]]\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien_Lesna"}
{"title_page": "Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s\n| image         = Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s (1954).jpg\n| fullname      = Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1922|12|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=y|2005|7|19|1922|12|30}}\n| death_place   = [[Cannes]], [[France]]\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9 (1949)\n}}\n\n'''Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s''' ([[Athens]], [[Greece]], 30 December 1922 \u2014 [[Cannes]], 19 July 2005) was a [[France|French]] professional [[road bicycle racer]]. Lazarid\u00e8s was born with [[Greeks|Greek]] nationality but became French in 1929. Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s was an older brother of cyclist [[Apo Lazarid\u00e8s]]. Lazarid\u00e8s won the Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9 in 1949 and reached the podium of the [[Tour de France]] in 1951. Later in his career he won two Tour de France stages.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1949\n:Nice - Mont Agel\n:[[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n;1951\n:[[1951 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::3rd place overall classification\n;1954\n:[[1954 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 17\n;1955\n:[[1955 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cycling archives|3434}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070807000226/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/3112.html Official Tour de France results for Lucien Lazarides]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lazarides, Lucien}}\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:French people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1920s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s\n| image         = Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s (1954).jpg\n| fullname      = Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1922|12|30}}\n| birth_place   = [[Athens]], [[Greece]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=y|2005|7|19|1922|12|30}}\n| death_place   = [[Cannes]], [[France]]\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9 (1949)\n}}\n\n'''Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s''' ([[Athens]], [[Greece]], 30 December 1922 \u2014 [[Cannes]], 19 July 2005) was a [[France|French]] professional [[road bicycle racer]]. Lazarid\u00e8s was born with [[Greeks|Greek]] nationality but became French in 1929. Lucien Lazarid\u00e8s was an older brother of cyclist [[Apo Lazarid\u00e8s]]. Lazarid\u00e8s won the Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9 in 1949 and reached the podium of the [[Tour de France]] in 1951. Later in his career he won two Tour de France stages.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1949\n:Nice - Mont Agel\n:[[Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9|Crit\u00e9rium du Dauphin\u00e9 Lib\u00e9r\u00e9]]\n;1951\n:[[1951 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::3rd place overall classification\n;1954\n:[[1954 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 17\n;1955\n:[[1955 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Winner stage 10\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{cycling archives|3434}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070807000226/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/riders/us/3112.html Official Tour de France results for Lucien Lazarides]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lazarides, Lucien}}\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:French Tour de France stage winners]]\n[[Category:French people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1920s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien_Lazarid%C3%A8s"}
{"title_page": "Sainthwar", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n'''Sainthwar''', also known as '''Mall''',<ref>{{cite book |author=Subodh Kapoor |title=Encyclopaedia of Ancient Indian Geography |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8897ridkczoC&pg=PA413%7Cyear%3D2002%7Cpublisher%3DCosmo+Publications%7Cisbn%3D978-81-7755-299-7%7Cpages%3D413%E2%80%93%7D%7D%3C%2Fref%3E |year=2002 |publisher=Cosmo |isbn=978-81-7755-299-7 |page=413 }}</ref> is an [[Indian caste]] of peasants<ref name=\"Shahid_1995\">{{cite book |author=Shahid Amin |title=Event, Metaphor, Memory: Chauri Chaura, 1922-1992 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pbYwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA33 |year=1995 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=978-0-520-08780-4 |page=33 |quote=Sainthwar: a middle-ranking caste of 'industrious' peasants, closely related to the Kurmi}}</ref> native to the [[Uttar Pradesh]] state.<ref name=\"KSS_OUP_1998\">{{cite book |editor=Kumar Suresh Singh |title=India's Communities |volume=A-G |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g9MVAQAAMAAJ |year=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-563354-2 |page=2163 }}</ref>\n\nThe Sainthwars are closely related to the  [[Kurmi]]s,<ref name=\"Shahid_1995\"/> and are sometimes described as a division of the Kurmi caste.<ref name=\"Paul_1987\">{{cite book |editor1=Paul R. Brass |editor2=Francis Robinson |title=The Indian National Congress and Indian society, 1885-1985: ideology, social structure, and political dominance |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9BJuAAAAMAAJ |year=1987 |publisher=Chanakya }}</ref> The Sainthwars are known as \"Mall\" (\"prosperous\") as opposed to the historically poorer Kurmis.<ref name=\"KSS_OUP_1998\"/> They are the dominant landholding caste in some districts of Uttar Pradesh.<ref name=\"Paul_1987\"/>\n\nThe oral tradition of the Sainthwars traces their ancestry to Chandraketu, a son of the legendary hero [[Lakshmana]].<ref name=\"KSS_OUP_1998\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n\n{{India-ethno-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sainthwar''' are a well-known and one of the prominent \"Kshatriya\" caste of Eastern UP . The word '''Sainthwar''' is derived from ancient word [[Santhagara]].  Sainthwar are one of the largest landholding community of eastern UP.They are mainly concentrated in the districts of Terai region of Eastern UP viz [[Gorakhpur]] , [[Kushinagar]] , [[Deoria]] , [[Maharajganj district|Maharajganj]] , [[Sant Kabir nagar]] and [[Mau]]. Agriculture is the main occupation of Sainthwar. The community consists of Big Zamindars(Land-holders) as well as small farmers.The biggest Zamindar of this community is the Raja of Padrauna state [[R. P. N. Singh]] who belongs to Padrauna Sainthwar rulers family.<ref name=\":0\" >{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Battles-Royal-in-Hindi-heartland/articleshow/4257903.cms|title=Battles 'Royal' in Hindi heartland - Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nA popular sect of this community claim Gautam buddha belongs to Sainthwar clan who is a pioneer figure of world.  Sainthwar are the one of the most educated community in Eastern UP and in the arena of Northern purvanchal sainthwar are known as Brain producers. The community consists of ancient ruler dynasties [[Malla (India)]], [[Shakya]], [[Koliya]], Mauryas Kshatriya of Pippali Vana, etc.<ref>Dr. [[Rajbali Pandey]] (1946) \"Gorakhpur Janpad aur Uski Kshatriya Jatiyo ka Itihaas\", ''[[Gorakhpur Janpad aur Uski Kshatriya Jatiyo ka Itihaas]]'', Re-Published 2015</ref> Some of the clans in the sainthwar kshatriya sangh \nbelongs to the [[Mahabat Khan]]'s rebel against [[Jahangir]] in 1626, who were get settled with the help of Raja Nathu Mall of Majhauli in the gorakhpur.\n\n==History==\n[[Sainthwar]] kshatriya are the descendant's of Santhagarik Kshatriya of [[Ga\u1e47a sangha|Gana-Rajya]]. These kshatriyas are also called vratya kshatriya. [[Gautama Buddha]] was born in this kshatriya sangh. Sainthwar Kshatriya Sangh supported the religious reform using Buddha and Jain philosophy. They are not the strict follower of Vedic Dharma. They did not give too much importance to Kul Devi and Ved (excluding some exception). That is the reason why they are called vratya kshatriya in [[Manu Smriti]].  The Ganarajya  (which is now Eastern Uttar Pradesh) constitutes the following republics: \n[[Shakya|Shakya Republic]], [[Malla (India)|Malla Republic]], Mauryas Kshatriya of Pippali Vana, [[Koliya | Koliya Republic of Ramgram]]. The Gana sangha is established by the descendant's of Angad and Chandraketu Mall (both are the son of [[Lakshmana]]). There is another Gana Sangha ([[Videha]] | Videha of [[Videha|Mithila]], [[Licchavi (clan)|Licchavis of Vaishali]] and other two) in Bihar. The both Gana-sangh had intense relationship in polity, religion, social reform, religious reform, political reform, etc. [[India|Republic of India (Bh\u0101rat Ga\u1e47ar\u0101jya)]] ancient democratic history is created by these Gana-sangha.\n==Controversy==\nIn 90s OBC commission found inadequate representation of Sainthwar in various field especially in Administration and Politics and granted OBC status for Sainthwar.\nOBC status proves a boon for sainthwar but simultaneously that fuel a major controversy among sainthwar because of word Kurmi- sainthwar.\n==Historical Figure==\n*[[Lakshmana]], Brother of Lord [[Rama]]\n*[[Gautama Buddha]]\n*[[Mahavira]]\n*[[Chandragupta Maurya]]\n*[[Ashoka|Samrat Ashoka]]\n\n== [[Chauri Chaura incident]]==\nThere are six sainthwar who were involved in [[Chauri Chaura incident]].<ref>Subhash Chandra Kushwaha \"Chauri Chaura : Vidroh Aur Swadhinta Andolan\", ''[[Chauri Chaura : Vidroh Aur Swadhinta Andolan]]'' {{ISBN|9780143422297}}</ref> These are people who burnt the Chauri Chaura police station in which 23 policeman were died. \n* Mahabir Singh Sainthwar (age 32) and Ramsaran Singh Sainthwar (age 25) s/o Lalsa Singh Sainthwar of Dumari Khurd (Chhotaki Dumari) village\n* Naifiqir Singh Sainthwar (age 25) s/o Chandra J Singh Sainthwar of Dumari Khurd (Chhotaki Dumari) village\n* Balbhadra Singh Sainthwar (age 25) s/o Mahabir Singh Sainthwar of Burhadih village\n* Sadhu Saran Singh Sainthwar (age 40) s/o Mohar Singh Sainthwar of Dumari Khurd (Chhotaki Dumari) village\n* Sheobaran Singh Sainthwar (age 55) s/o Mathura Singh Sainthwar of Bharatpur village\n\n==Political People==\n* Late Akshaibar Singh,Ex MLA\n* Late Chandrabali Singh, Ex MLA \n* Late Kedarnath Singh, Ex MLA Pipraich\n* Late Rajesh Singh Sainthwar\n* Late Sugriv Singh, Ex MLA\n* Nand Kishore Singh, Ex MLA\n* Devnarayan Singh alias GM Singh, Ex MLA\n* Ravindra Pratap Mall\n* Janmejay Singh, MLA Deoria\n* Mahendra Pal Singh Sainthwar, MLA Pipraich\n* Gyanendra Singh, MLA Paniyara\n* Virendra Singh Sainthwar, Leader BSP\n* Kishan Singh Sainthwar,Leader SP\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}} \n{{coord missing|Uttar Pradesh}}\n\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "restore to last undamaged version; rv unref/unjustified changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sainthwar"}
{"title_page": "Lucien Lauk", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Lucien Lauk\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1911|6|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2001|6|8|1911|6|29|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Paris, France\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''Lucien Lauk''' (29 June 1911 &ndash; 8 June 2001) was a French [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]]. He rode in the [[1948 Tour de France]].<ref name=\"mdc1948\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1948.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=35\u00e8me Tour de France 1948|language=French|accessdate=7 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301034216/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1948.php|archivedate=1 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|10900}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauk, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1910s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Lucien Lauk\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1911|6|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|2001|6|8|1911|6|29|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Paris, France\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n| updated        = \n}}\n'''Lucien Lauk''' (29 June 1911 &ndash; 8 June 2001) was a French [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]]. He rode in the [[1948 Tour de France]].<ref name=\"mdc1948\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1948.php|publisher=Memoire du cyclisme|title=35\u00e8me Tour de France 1948|language=French|accessdate=7 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301034216/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1947_1977/tdf1948.php|archivedate=1 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cycling archives|10900}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lauk, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n{{France-cycling-bio-1910s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien_Lauk"}
{"title_page": "Athletics Ireland", "text_new": "{{short description|Governing body for athletics on the island of Ireland}}\n{{Infobox sport governing body\n|name         = Athletics Ireland (Athletics Association of Ireland)\n|abbrev       = AAI\n|logo         =\n|logosize     = \n|sport        = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]\n|category     =\n|image        = \n|caption      =\n|jurisdiction = \n|founded      = 1937\n|aff          = [[IAAF]]\n|affdate      = \n|region       = [[European Athletic Association|EAA]]\n|regionyear   = \n|headquarters = [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]\n|location     = \n|president    = [[Georgina Drumm]]\n|chairman     =\n|chairperson  =\n|chair        =\n|chiefexec    =\n|vicepresident =  \n|secretary    = [[Hamish Adams]]\n|coach        =\n|womenscoach  =\n|key staff    =\n|operating income =\n|sponsor      = \n|year closed  =\n|replaced     = \n|prevfounded  = \n|url          = https://www.athleticsireland.ie/\n|countryflag  = Ireland\n|countryflag2 =\n|countryflag3 =\n|more         = \n}}\n\n'''Athletics Ireland''', officially the ''Athletics Association of Ireland'' or AAI, is the governing body for athletics in Ireland, with athletics defined as including track and field athletics, road running, race walking, cross country running, mountain running and ultra distance running. The organisation's jurisdiction covers the whole island of Ireland and it is affiliated to the International Association of Athletic Federations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/athleticassociationconstitution.pdf |title=Constitution of the Athletic Association of Ireland |publisher=Athletic Association of Ireland |accessdate=September 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329133837/http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/athleticassociationconstitution.pdf |archivedate=March 29, 2012 }}</ref>  Its remit is to promote athletics from recreational running, schools competitions and to support elite athletes in international competitions.<ref name=\"oireachtas\">{{cite web | url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/parliament/mediazone/pressreleases/name-2048-en.html | title=President of Athletics Association of Ireland to appear before Committee on Tourism, Culture, Sport, Community, Equality and Gaeltacht Affairs | publisher=House of the Oireachteas | accessdate=September 8, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607081330/http://www.oireachtas.ie/parliament/mediazone/pressreleases/name-2048-en.html | archive-date=June 7, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe association has provincial councils in each of Ireland's four provinces, and county boards in the majority of Ireland's 32 traditional counties.\n\n==History==\n{{details|National Athletic and Cycling Association}}\n\nThe AAI  in its present form was established in 2000, but the history of sports governing bodies in Ireland is complicated because of the partition of the country in 1923.  In 1884 the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) was formed and the Irish Amateur Athletic Association (IAAA) was formed in 1885. The Cross County Association of Ireland (CCAI) was established in 1886 and later became a subsidiary of the IAAA.  In 1923 the [[National Athletic and Cycling Association]] (NACA) was established merging the IAAA, the CCAI,  and the Athletics Council of the GAA, with the GAA thenceforth concentrating on [[Gaelic games]]. The NACA was then admitted to membership of the [[IAAF]]. In July 1924 the Northern Ireland Amateur Athletic, Cycling and Cross Country Association (NIAAA) was formed over a dispute concerning an Easter Monday athletics meeting in Belfast, breaking away from the NACA. The Amateur Athletic Association (AAA) accepted this breakaway group under its jurisdiction.\n\nThe IAAF adopted an amendment to its constitution in 1930 which defined member organisations as being contiguous with political entities. The NACA rejected this ruling and was suspended from the IAAF. In 1937 some clubs seceded from the NACA to set up the Irish Amateur Athletic Union (IAAU) and this body became a member of the IAAF the following year while the NACA's suspension was made permanent. NACA later changed their name to the National Athletic and Cultural Association of Ireland (NACAI).\n\nThe IAAU became the Amateur Athletic Union of Eire (AAUE) which represented Ireland at subsequent Olympic games. In 1967 Bord L\u00fathchleas na h\u00c9ireann (BLE) was formed. \n\nIn 1987, and with improved north-south relations,  BLE and NACAI signed an agreement allowing athletes affiliated to both bodies to represent Ireland.  BLE and NACAI dissolved completely in 2000 to form the Athletics Association of Ireland (Athletics Ireland).<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web | url=http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/?page_id=5990 | title=History | publisher=Athletics Ireland | accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Kit suppliers==\nIreland's kits are currently supplied by Spanish sports brand Joma Sport. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.athleticsireland.ie/ Official website]\n\n{{National Members of the International Association of Athletics Federations}}\n{{National Members of the European Athletic Association}}\n{{Sports governing bodies in Ireland}}\n\n[[Category:National members of the European Athletic Association|Ireland]]\n[[Category:All-island sports governing bodies in Ireland|Athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletics in Ireland| ]]\n[[Category:National governing bodies for athletics]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 2000]]\n\n{{Ireland-sport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Governing body for athletics on the island of Ireland}}\n{{Infobox sport governing body\n|name         = Athletics Ireland (Athletics Association of Ireland)\n|abbrev       = AAI\n|logo         =\n|logosize     = \n|sport        = [[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]\n|category     =\n|image        = \n|caption      =\n|jurisdiction = \n|founded      = 1937\n|aff          = [[IAAF]]\n|affdate      = \n|region       = [[European Athletic Association|EAA]]\n|regionyear   = \n|headquarters = [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]\n|location     = \n|president    = [[Georgina Drumm]]\n|chairman     =\n|chairperson  =\n|chair        =\n|chiefexec    =\n|vicepresident =  \n|secretary    = [[Hamish Adams]]\n|coach        =\n|womenscoach  =\n|key staff    =\n|operating income =\n|sponsor      = \n|year closed  =\n|replaced     = \n|prevfounded  = \n|url          = https://www.athleticsireland.ie/\n|countryflag  = Ireland\n|countryflag2 =\n|countryflag3 =\n|more         = \n}}\n\n'''Athletics Ireland''', officially the ''Athletics Association of Ireland'' or AAI, is the governing body for athletics in Ireland, with athletics defined as including track and field athletics, road running, race walking, cross country running, mountain running and ultra distance running. The organisation's jurisdiction covers the whole island of Ireland and it is affiliated to the International Association of Athletic Federations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/athleticassociationconstitution.pdf |title=Constitution of the Athletic Association of Ireland |publisher=Athletic Association of Ireland |accessdate=September 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329133837/http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/wp-content/uploads/2009/04/athleticassociationconstitution.pdf |archivedate=March 29, 2012 }}</ref>  Its remit is to promote athletics from recreational running, schools competitions and to support elite athletes in international competitions.<ref name=\"oireachtas\">{{cite web | url=http://www.oireachtas.ie/parliament/mediazone/pressreleases/name-2048-en.html | title=President of Athletics Association of Ireland to appear before Committee on Tourism, Culture, Sport, Community, Equality and Gaeltacht Affairs | publisher=House of the Oireachteas | accessdate=September 8, 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607081330/http://www.oireachtas.ie/parliament/mediazone/pressreleases/name-2048-en.html | archive-date=June 7, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Structure==\nThe association has provincial councils in each of Ireland's four provinces, and county boards in the majority of Ireland's 32 traditional counties.\n\n==History==\n{{details|National Athletic and Cycling Association}}\n\nThe AAI  in its present form was established in 2000, but the history of sports governing bodies in Ireland is complicated because of the partition of the country in 1923.  In 1884 the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) was formed and the Irish Amateur Athletic Association (IAAA) was formed in 1885. The Cross County Association of Ireland (CCAI) was established in 1886 and later became a subsidiary of the IAAA.  In 1923 the [[National Athletic and Cycling Association]] (NACA) was established merging the IAAA, the CCAI,  and the Athletics Council of the GAA, with the GAA thenceforth concentrating on [[Gaelic games]]. The NACA was then admitted to membership of the [[IAAF]]. In July 1924 the Northern Ireland Amateur Athletic, Cycling and Cross Country Association (NIAAA) was formed over a dispute concerning an Easter Monday athletics meeting in Belfast, breaking away from the NACA. The Amateur Athletic Association (AAA) accepted this breakaway group under its jurisdiction.\n\nThe IAAF adopted an amendment to its constitution in 1930 which defined member organisations as being contiguous with political entities. The NACA rejected this ruling and was suspended from the IAAF. In 1937 some clubs seceded from the NACA to set up the Irish Amateur Athletic Union (IAAU) and this body became a member of the IAAF the following year while the NACA's suspension was made permanent. NACA later changed their name to the National Athletic and Cultural Association of Ireland (NACAI).\n\nThe IAAU became the Amateur Athletic Union of Eire (AAUE) which represented Ireland at subsequent Olympic games. In 1967 Bord L\u00fathchleas na h\u00c9ireann (BLE) was formed. \n\nIn 1987, and with improved north-south relations,  BLE and NACAI (signed an agreement allowing athletes affiliated to both bodies to represent Ireland.  BLE and NACAI dissolved completely in 2000 to form the Athletics Association of Ireland (Athletics Ireland).<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web | url=http://www.athleticsireland.ie/content/?page_id=5990 | title=History | publisher=Athletics Ireland | accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Kit suppliers==\nIreland's kits are currently supplied by Spanish sports brand Joma Sport. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.athleticsireland.ie/ Official website]\n\n{{National Members of the International Association of Athletics Federations}}\n{{National Members of the European Athletic Association}}\n{{Sports governing bodies in Ireland}}\n\n[[Category:National members of the European Athletic Association|Ireland]]\n[[Category:All-island sports governing bodies in Ireland|Athletics]]\n[[Category:Athletics in Ireland| ]]\n[[Category:National governing bodies for athletics]]\n[[Category:Sports organizations established in 2000]]\n\n{{Ireland-sport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kearneybrendanb", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athletics_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Lucien Faucheux", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Lucien Faucheux\n| image         = Lucien Faucheux.jpg\n| caption       = Faucheux in 1929\n| fullname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1899|8|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Le Kremlin-Bic\u00eatre]], France\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1980|7|22|1899|8|26|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Bordeaux]], France\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Lucien Faucheux''' (26 August 1899 &ndash; 22 July 1980) was a French [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|men's team pursuit event]] at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fa/lucien-faucheux-1.html |title=Lucien Faucheux Olympic Results |accessdate=2013-12-25 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faucheux, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Lucien Faucheux\n| image         = Lucien Faucheux.jpg\n| caption       = Faucheux in 1929\n| fullname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1899|8|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Le Kremlin-Bic\u00eatre]], France\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1980|7|22|1899|8|26|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Bordeaux]], France\n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Lucien Faucheux''' (26 August 1899 &ndash; 22 July 1980) was a French [[cycling|cyclist]]. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1920 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|men's team pursuit event]] at the [[1920 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/fa/lucien-faucheux-1.html |title=Lucien Faucheux Olympic Results |accessdate=2013-12-25 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faucheux, Lucien}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of France]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1920 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucien_Faucheux"}
